description: A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomy was traveling west on 16th Street in the left travel lane, slowing as it approached the intersection with Utah Street in San Francisco. The Zoox vehicle operator disengaged from autonomy and braked further for stopped traffic ahead in the same travel lane. At that time, a Tesla sedan (Vehicle 2) traveling directly behind the Zoox vehicle abruptly attempted a lane change maneuver into the adjacent lane on the right,  side-swiping a BMW sedan (Vehicle 3) that was also westbound on 16th Street in the right lane. Vehicle 2, after making contact with Vehicle 3, veered back to the left lane behind the Zoox vehicle and rear ended the stopped Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage, while Vehicle 2 and Vehicle 3 appeared to have sustained moderate damage. There were no reported injuries and the police were not called.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomy was traveling west on 16th Street in the left travel lane, slowing as it approached the intersection with Utah Street in San Francisco. The Zoox vehicle the operator disengaged from autonomy and braked further for stopped traffic ahead in the same travel lane. At that time, a Tesla sedan (Vehicle 2) traveling directly behind the Zoox vehicle abruptly attempted a lane change maneuver into the adjacent lane on the right,  side-swiping a BMW sedan (Vehicle 3) that was also westbound on 16th Street in the right lane. Vehicle 2, after making contact with Vehicle 3, veered back to the left lane behind the Zoox vehicle and rear ended the stopped Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage, while Vehicle 2 and Vehicle 3 appeared to have sustained moderate damage. There were no reported injuries and the police were not called.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1), was completing a mission traveling southwest on Division Street in San Francisco. As the vehicle was completing its mission and slowed to a near stop, the Zoox vehicle operator identified an oncoming bicycle, disengaged from autonomy, and braked the Zoox vehicle to a full stop in its lane. The bicyclist crossed into the oncoming traffic lane occupied by the Zoox vehicle and continued rapidly while steering directly towards the front of the Zoox vehicle. The bicycle made contact with the front bumper of the stationary Zoox vehicle and the bicyclist made contact with the hood of the Zoox vehicle and fell to the ground. The police and emergency responders arrived at the scene and the bicyclist was transported to a hospital. Preliminary police information describes injuries to the bicyclist as “loss of consciousness, complaint of pain to back, knee, and toe nail”.

On July 19, 2024 at 1:26 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in Mountain View, California was in a collision involving a curb in a parking lot near 65 Alta Avenue.The Waymo AV was traveling through a parking lot when it drove over a curb and the bottom of the Waymo AV made contact with the curb. At the time of the contact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.

On July 18, 2024 at 5:41 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on Bush Street at Market Street. 

The Waymo AV was stopped facing a green traffic light on southeastbound Bush Street at the intersection with Market Street to yield to a traffic control officer who was directing traffic in the crosswalk. While the Waymo AV remained stopped and the traffic light turned yellow, an SUV that had been stopped behind the Waymo AV approached the Waymo AV and made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. When the traffic light ahead of the Waymo AV turned green and the Waymo AV remained stopped, the SUV reversed briefly and then changed lanes into the left adjacent lane to maneuver around the Waymo AV, making contact with the rear driver side corner of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impacts, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage, and the SUV left the scene.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomous mode was stopped at a stop sign waiting for traffic to clear to make a left turn from northeast bound King Street onto 7th Street in San Francisco. A passenger car (Vehicle 2) was stopped  directly behind the Zoox vehicle apparently in the process of turning right onto 7th Street. As the Zoox vehicle advanced and then came to a stop as it yielded to cross traffic, the passenger car tried to pass the Zoox vehicle on the right side and contacted the Zoox vehicle. The front bumper on the passenger car and rear bumper on the Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage. There were no reported injuries and the police were not called.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1), operating in manual mode, was traveling north on Bryant Street toward 16th Street in San Francisco. The Zoox vehicle was stopped behind traffic for a red traffic signal. After a few seconds, just as the traffic signal turned green and before the Zoox vehicle started to move, it was rear ended by a rapidly approaching passenger car (Vehicle 2). The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage and the police were not called. There were no reported injuries.

On July 2, 2024 at 3:09 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a pickup truck on Sycamore Avenue near W. Pico Boulevard. The Waymo AV was traveling northbound on Sycamore Avenue when it came to a stop to yield to an oncoming pickup truck in a narrow roadway with parked vehicles on both sides of the street. As the oncoming pickup truck passed the stopped Waymo AV, the front driver’s side of the pickup truck made contact with the driver’s side rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage and the pickup truck left the scene.

At 3:51pm, a WeRide vehicle (Car1) was attempting to make a u-turn at 6 mph on Northwestern parkway. During the u-turn maneuver, a white chevy cruze (Car 2) traveling at 23 mph, having just made a right turn off of Walsh Ave., approached from behind on northwestern parkway. Car 2 steered left just before the impact but still clipped the front left side bumper of Car 1 with its (car2's) right side. The damage sustained to Car 1 was on the front bumper, left side, and the damage sustained to Car 2 was on the right passenger's door. Both parties pulled over to exchange information. The other party vehicle owner (of car2), Sagardeep Singh. was not driving the vehicle but was seated in the front passenger seat and Gurdeep Singh was driving the vehicle at the time of accident.
There were no injuries reported and no emergency responders were called.

On June 11, 2024 at 12:07 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Santa Monica, California was in a collision involving an SUV on Maple Street near 10th Street. The Waymo AV was maneuvering out of a curbside parallel parking space at the curb on the south side of Maple Street when the passenger side front corner of the Waymo AV made contact with the driver side back corner of an SUV parked in front of the AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.

At approximately 10:33am, a WeRide vehicle (car 1) was stopped at a red traffic light on E San Carlos st. about to turn right on S 4th St. At this time a Toyota RAV4 (car 2) approached from behind traveling at a speed of (>10mph) and slammed into car 1's rear - causing damages to car 1. Car 1 sustained damages on rear bumper and rear sensors. Both parties pulled over to a safe location to exchange information. Car 2's driver didn't have an up-to-date registration card for the vehicle.

On June 5, 2024 at 1:12 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on 29th Avenue near Lawton Street.The Waymo AV was parked at the curb on the right side of 29th Avenue when a passenger car in front of the Waymo AV began to reverse to parallel park. The passenger car’s rear driver side corner made contact with the front driver side corner of the parked Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.

On June 4, 2024 at 6:26 PM PT  a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on Lombard Street at Fillmore Street. The Waymo AV was stopped in traffic for a red light on eastbound Lombard Street when an SUV traveling at a high rate of speed changed lanes and approached the Waymo AV from behind. The front of the SUV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.

On June 3, 2024 at 4:54 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in Marina Del Rey, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on Admiralty Way at Bali Way. The Waymo AV was making a left turn from the rightmost dedicated left turn lane on Admiralty Way into lane two of three lanes in the eastbound direction of Bali Way. A passenger car was also making a left turn from the leftmost dedicated left turn lane (leftmost lane). The passenger car had made the turn onto Bali Way and was partially in the number 1 lane (leftmost) and partially in the number 2 lane (middle) when the front passenger side of the passenger car made contact with the rear driver side of the Waymo AV, which was traveling in the number 2 lane (middle). At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver’s seating position). Both vehicles sustained damage.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomy was traveling westbound on Chess Drive in Foster City when a parallel-parked passenger car (Vehicle 2) abruptly entered the Zoox vehicle’s travel lane from a parking space in the right parking lane without yielding or activating a turn signal. Vehicle 2 made contact with the right front side and wheel of the Zoox vehicle, and the Zoox vehicle made contact with the driver side door and left front tire/wheel well of the passenger car. Both vehicles sustained moderate damage and the Zoox vehicle was towed from the scene. There were no injuries and police were not called.

On Wednesday, May 22, 2024 at approximately 3:45pm PST, a Nuro Prius operating in manual mode bumped a pedestrian at the
intersection of Webster Street and Middlefield Road in Palo Alto, California.

The Nuro Prius was in autonomous mode when it approached the intersection and came to a stop at the stop bar on Webster Street. It is
a two-way stop with the traffic on Middlefield having right of way. The Nuro Prius nudged forward due to an occlusion.The Nuro operator judged the nudging to be too far and disengaged autonomous mode to reverse in manual. When reversing, the operator bumped a pedestrian crossing the street behind the Nuro Prius. 

The pedestrian was not injured and after speaking with the operator, left the scene without providing additional information. There was no damage to the vehicle and law enforcement was not involved.

On May 20, 2024 at 3:02 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on 14th Street at Folsom Street. The Waymo AV was traveling east on 14th Street and came to a stop at a red light at the intersection with Folsom Street to prepare for a left turn. When the light turned green, the Waymo AV proceeded into the intersection. As it did so, a passenger car traveling southbound on Folsom Street at a high rate of speed entered the intersection against a red traffic light. The front of the passenger car made contact with the driver’s side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage, and the passengers of the passenger car left the scene on foot.

On May 17, 2024 at 11:45 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on Interstate 280 North between exits 54B and 55. The Waymo AV was traveling north on Interstate 280 in the rightmost lane in autonomous mode with a test driver seated in the driver's seated position when it approached a slow-moving heavy truck equipped with a truck-mounted light matrix displaying a yellow arrow indicating that traffic should merge to the left. The Waymo AV slowed down behind the heavy truck and the test driver transitioned the Waymo AV to manual mode. The test driver stopped the Waymo AV and activated the left turn signal. Several vehicles passed the Waymo AV on the left side before the test driver manually initiated a left lane change, and the front passenger side of a passenger car which was passing the Waymo AV on the left made contact with the front driver side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode.  Both vehicles sustained damage.

On May 15, 2024, the front right bumper of a Pony.ai autonomous vehicle (AV) scraped against a flexible plastic traffic pylon on Auto Mall Pkwy near the intersection of Auto Mall Pkwy & Grimmer Blvd, in Fremont, CA. The vehicle was operating in supervised autonomous (“Drivered”)  mode. There were no other vehicles, pedestrians, or road users involved.Following the incident, the safety operator pulled over in a safe location and confirmed there was only minor cosmetic damage to the front bumper of the AV. The safety operator then promptly drove the vehicle, in manual mode, to Pony.ai’s Fremont office. There were no injuries, and the police were not called.

On May 13, 2024 at 12:58 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, CA was in a collision involving a passenger car on eastbound Interstate 10 between Exit 2 and Exit 3A. The Waymo AV was traveling with a test driver present behind a box truck in the number 3 lane of eastbound Interstate 10 near the Bundy Drive overpass when a passenger car traveling at a high rate of speed approached the Waymo AV from behind. The passenger car partially entered the number 2 lane as the front right corner of the passenger car made contact with the rear left corner of the Waymo AV. The passenger car then made contact with the center median and came to a stop. The Waymo AV was transitioned into manual mode, and the test driver stopped the Waymo AV to the right-hand shoulder. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver’s seating position). Both vehicles sustained damage.

On May 8, 2024 at 11:16 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a wild animal (raccoon) on Interstate 280 Junipero Serra Freeway between exits 49B and 51. The Waymo AV was traveling eastbound on Interstate 280 in autonomous mode when a raccoon ran into the roadway from the left side of the highway in front of the Waymo AV. The Waymo AV test driver transitioned to manual mode shortly before the front driver’s side of the Waymo AV made contact with the raccoon. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomy was stopped at a red light in the right travel lane on southbound 11th Street at the intersection with Bryant/Division Streets in San Francisco. After the light turned green, the Zoox vehicle entered the intersection and began bearing right onto southbound Bryant Street when a lane-splitting motorcycle (Vehicle 2) operator maneuvered around other traffic and quickly came up on the rear of the Zoox vehicle, traversing laterally in lane from the left to the right side of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle braked and then the Zoox vehicle operator disengaged. The motorcycle then struck the passenger’s side of the rear bumper and quarter panel on the Zoox vehicle and the motorcycle and its operator fell to the ground. The motorcycle operator appeared to have scraped his hands, but declined medical attention. The motorcycle sustained minor damage to the fairing, left side mirror, and front and rear left turn signal lens and the Zoox vehicle did not sustain damage. The motorcycle operator left the scene without exchanging their information. The police were not called.

On April 23, 2024, a Pony.ai autonomous vehicle (AV) scraped a curb on Lakeview Blvd near the intersection of Lakeview Blvd & Gateway Blvd in Fremont, CA. The vehicle was operating in supervised autonomous ("Drivered") mode. There were no other vehicles, pedestrians, or road users involved.Following the incident, the safety operator promptly drove the AV, in manual mode, to Pony.ai's Fremont office. There were no injuriesreported, and the police were not called.

A Zoox vehicle, operating in manual mode, was traveling north on Folsom Street, preparing to turn left onto 21st Street in San Francisco when the front wheel on the driver's side rode over a traffic island to the left side of the Zoox vehicle. The sidewall of the tire was damaged as a result of the interaction. There were no reported injuries and the police were not called.

On April 13, 2024 at 3:35 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a pickup truck on Bayshore Boulevard near Boutwell Street. The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on Bayshore Boulevard in the far right lane when it passed a pickup truck that was stopped in the bike lane. As the Waymo passed the pickup truck, the driver of the pickup truck opened the driver’s side door and the door made contact with the Waymo’s passenger side wing mirror and rear right sensor housing.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained damage.

On April 11, 2024 at 10:14 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on Vallejo Street at Stockton Street. The Waymo AV was traveling westbound on Vallejo Street and stopped at a red light. A heavy truck was turning left onto Vallejo Street from Stockton Street. As the heavy truck approached, the Waymo AV started to slowly reverse to make more space. The test driver transitioned to manual, and the driver’s side of the heavy truck and the driver's side front corner of the Waymo AV made contact. The heavy truck left the scene. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.

A Zoox vehicle in autonomy, traveling westbound on 3rd Avenue toward Foster City Blvd in Foster City drove over an in-lane utility valve box with a displaced valve cover. The Zoox vehicle sustained damage to the undercarriage. There were no reported injuries and police were not called.

On March 30, 2024 at 1:33 AM PT, a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on Jerrold Avenue at Barneveld Avenue.The Waymo AV was stopped at a stop sign on Jerrold Avenue and yielding to a pickup truck that was in the intersection making a left turnfrom Barneveld Avenue onto Jerrold Avenue when the front right corner of the SUV, which was traveling behind the Waymo AV, madecontact with the rear left corner of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomousmode. Both vehicles sustained damage.

On March 28, 2024 at 7:30 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on Louisiana Avenue at Kerwood Avenue. While making a tight left turn from southbound Kerwood Avenue onto northeastbound Louisiana Avenue, the Waymo AV made contact with the driver side of a parked passenger car. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver’s seating position). Both vehicles sustained damage.

On March 22, 2024 at 08:00 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car near the 200 block of Church Street before Market Street. The Waymo AV was traveling north on Church Street towards the intersection with Market Street when it came to a stop behind an SUV which was stopped in-lane to load passengers. Another SUV approached from behind the Waymo AV and came to a stop. The lead SUV finished loading passengers and proceeded forward to the stop line at Market Street, and the Waymo AV proceeded forward as well. The trailing SUV proceeded forward and the front of the SUV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage and the SUV left the scene.

On March 19, 2024 at 7:18 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on Division Street at 9th Street. The Waymo AV was traveling west on Division Street after having stopped at the stop sign at Vermont Street and was approaching the intersection with 9th Street when a passenger car approached from behind the Waymo AV, ran the stop sign at Vermont Street, and made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. The front of the passenger car made continuous contact with the rear of the Waymo AV while both vehicles were still in motion for a short period of time before the passenger car slowed down and separated from the AV. The Waymo AV proceeded through the intersection with 9th Street and came to a stop on Division Street west of the intersection with 9th Street. The passenger car then accelerated and the front right corner of the passenger car made contact with the rear left corner of the stationary Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1), operating in manual mode, was traveling northeast on 3rd Avenue toward Norfolk St in San Mateo. The Zoox vehicle was stopped in the right through lane behind traffic for a red traffic signal, when it was rear ended by a passenger car (Vehicle 2) that was traveling directly behind. There was no visible damage to either vehicle and the police were not called. The safety operator of the Zoox vehicle reported back pain a few days after the collision. Zoox vehicle camera footage shows that the driver of the passenger car may not have been looking ahead at the roadway prior to and at the time of contact.

On March 14, 2024 at 2:42 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on S Figueroa Street at 7th Street. The Waymo AV was traveling northeast on S Figueroa Street in the lane adjacent to the rightmost, bus-only lane. As the Waymo AV approached the intersection with 7th Street, it came to a stop behind another vehicle stopped in traffic. As a passenger car was passing the Waymo AV in the bus lane to the right of the Waymo AV, the passenger car made contact with the passenger side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage and the passenger car left the scene.Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.
vehicle_2_model: Toyota Avalon Limited / Touring / XL / XLS

description: On Tuesday, March 12th, a Nuro Prius vehicle operating in manual was turning left from Alvin Street onto Thompson Ave in Mountain View, California. The Prius vehicle bumped the medium and knocked over a white pylon. The vehicle had minor damage and no injuries were reported. No other vehicles or VRUs were involved. Law enforcement was not involved.

On March 8, 2024 at 12:06 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a passenger car near the 1600 block of S. Figueroa Street. The Waymo AV made a left turn from W. 17th Street onto S. Figueroa Street and came to a stop in a queue of stopped traffic. A passenger car traveling straight on S. Figueroa Street behind the Waymo AV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage and the passenger car left the scene.

On March 3, 2024 at 3:12 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a pick-up truck near the 2300 block of Cesar Chavez Street.The Waymo AV was traveling westbound on Cesar Chavez Street towards 26th Street when it approached a pick-up truck which was oriented with its rear partially in the roadway on the north side of Cesar Chavez street. The pick-up truck was stationary but its reverse lights were illuminated. The Waymo AV came to a stop momentarily to yield to the pick-up truck, then began moving again to pass the pick-up truck, which had remained stopped. After the Waymo AV started moving, the pick-up truck began reversing further out of the driveway and the rear of the pick-up truck made contact with the right side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver’s seating position). Both vehicles sustained damage.

On March 2, 2024 at 8:14 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a dumpster on Odd Fellows Way, at the rear garage exit of 1155 Market Street. The Waymo AV was making a reversing right turn out of the parking garage onto Odd Fellows Way when the rear left corner of the Waymo AV made contact with a dumpster which was next to the curb in the roadway opposite the garage exit.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomy, traveling northeast on Mission St, was stopped in lane for a red traffic light at 9th Street. A SamTrans bus (Vehicle 2), with a front-mounted triple-bike rack extending past the width of the bus on the driver's side, was traveling southeast on 9th Street and attempting a right turn onto Mission St. The protruding edge of the bike rack was encroaching into the Zoox vehicle's travel lane as the bus was executing the right hand turn. As the light turned green the Zoox vehicle inched forward and attempted to steer away from the bus. Just as the safety operator disengaged from autonomy, the protruding edge of the bike rack made contact with the driver's side fender on the Zoox vehicle. There were no reported injuries and the police were not called.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomy was traveling southwest on Harrison St and turning right onto 13th Street on a green traffic signal. While executing the turn, the Zoox vehicle braked to achieve a minimal risk condition due to an unexpected system fault, the safety operator disengaged, and then was rear ended by a passenger car (Vehicle 2) that was also turning directly behind the Zoox vehicle. The rear bumper cover and rear radar unit on the Zoox vehicle sustained damage. The hood, front grille and front bumper cover on the passenger car appeared to have sustained damage. There were no reported injuries and police were not called.

On February 18, 2024 at 1:03 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on The Embarcadero at Washington Street.The Waymo AV was stopped in traffic for a red light on The Embarcadero southbound when a passenger car approached from behind and made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). Both vehicles sustained damage and the passenger car left the scene.

On February 15th, a test vehicle operating with the automated driving system engaged was traveling Northbound on Highway 101 in Sunnyvale. The safety driver disengaged just prior to running over a piece of metal in the road. No injuries were reported and law enforcement was not called to the scene. The vehicle sustained minor damage.

On February 5, 2024 at 10:01 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a gate at Watt Way and West Exposition Boulevard.The Waymo AV was traveling south on Watt when it approached an automatic gate as it had started to close. The right side of the Waymo AV made contact with the door of the gate. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.

On January 31, 2024 at 5:15 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle on Potrero Avenue near 22nd Street.The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on Potrero Avenue in the leftmost thru lane, adjacent to a dedicated left turn lane on its left. As the Waymo AV approached the intersection with 22nd Street, it came to a stop behind its lead vehicle. The passenger vehicle behind the Waymo AV then attempted to change lanes into the dedicated left turn lane, and made contact with the rear driver side corner of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.
vehicle_2_model: Toyota Camry L / LE / SE / XLE

description: On Wednesday, January 31st at approximately 4:20pm, a Nuro Prius was operating in autonomous mode driving south on Boyce Ave in Palo Alto. As the Prius proceeded straight through the intersection of Boyce Ave. and Fife Ave. a Honda CR-V ran the Fife Ave. stop sign and initiated a left turn. The Honda CR-V rear-ended the Nuro Prius, though the Nuro driver took control of the Prius and nudged right in an attempt to avoid impact. Both vehicles sustained de minimis damage. Law enforcement was not involved and there were no injuries reported or VRUs present.

On January 26th, a test vehicle operating with the automated driving system engaged was traveling Eastbound on Interstate 580 in Castro Valley when a nearby semi-trailer truck merging from Interstate 238 generated a draft that projected road debris onto the test vehicle. No injuries were reported and law enforcement was not called to the scene. The test vehicle sustained minor damage.

At approximately 12:56pm, a WeRide vehicle (car 1) was slowing to a stop (< 3mph) on 2nd street at the intersection of East San Fernando st. to turn left in an effort to yield to crossing pedestrians. At this time a Toyota Prius (car 2) traveling (>10mph) had slammed into car 1's rear - causing damage primarily to car 1. Both parties pulled over to a safe location to exchange information but the driver of car 2 could not provide a valid insurance or registration certificate.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomy was traveling on southbound Stockton St near Union St in San Francisco. The Zoox vehicle slowed to a gradual stop with brake and hazard lights activated during a simulated pick up-drop off maneuver when it was rear-ended by a minivan (Vehicle 2). The rear bumper of the Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage. There were no reported injuries, and police were not called. Zoox vehicle camera footage shows that the driver of the minivan may not have been looking ahead at the roadway prior to and at the time of contact.

On Friday, January 12th, a Nuro Prius operating autonomously was stopped at a red light at the intersection of Shoreline and Terra Bella Ave. A Mazda approaching the intersection failed to completely stop and rear-ended the Nuro Prius. No injuries were reported. Both vehicles sustained minor damage.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1), operating in manual mode, was traveling southbound on Florida St near the intersection with Division St in San Francisco. The Zoox vehicle slowed to a stop to allow an oncoming box truck (Vehicle 2), attempting to turn left, to clear when the box truck made contact with the driver's side rear camera housing on the Zoox vehicle. There were no reported injuries and the police were not called.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1), operating in manual mode, was stopped for a red traffic light  on northbound Bryant St at the intersection with 6th St in San Francisco with an SUV (Vehicle 2) traveling directly behind . As the signal turned green the Zoox vehicle remained stopped to avoid blocking the intersection as traffic was still stopped ahead. The SUV proceeded to move into the adjacent left lane, when its front bumper on the passenger's side made contact with the driver's side rear bumper of the Zoox vehicle. The front bumper of the SUV appeared to have sustained minor damage. The driver of the SUV left the scene without exchanging information. There were no reported injuries and the police were not called.

A Ghost ADS-equipped car was driving engaged Northbound on Highway 17. As always, there were two safety drivers in the car. Traffic was moving in all four lanes at or near the speed limit. The Ghost vehicle was in the right-middle lane. Another vehicle (the "lead" car) entered into the Ghost car's lane from the right. While there were numerous vehicles ahead of the Ghost car before that vehicle entered the lane, the lead vehicle blocked the view of the lane before it. Throughout the incident, traffic in the other three lanes continued at a steady pace. When the lead vehicle entered into the lane ahead of the Ghost car, the Ghost car applied the brakes to accommodate the intrusion and then continued to match the speed of the lead car. The lead car suddenly slammed the brakes. The Ghost car followed suit, reducing its speed from 19 mps (42.5 mph) to 4.7 mps (10.5 mph) within the next three seconds. The Ghost car was able to match the rapid speed reduction of the lead car and avoid contact. The driver following the Ghost car was not able to respond as quickly as the Ghost ADS. When the following driver began to apply the brakes, the car was about five meters behind and was traveling at 6.5 mps. At the point of impact, the Ghost vehicle was traveling at 4.78 mps (10.7 mph), matching the lead car. There were no injuries. The vehicles suffered only cosmetic damage, the drivers exchanged information, and the Ghost safety drivers returned to home base in conventional mode.

On January 8, 2023 at 12:05 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (“Waymo AV”) operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving an SUV on Manhattan Place at West Adams Boulevard.  The Waymo AV was traveling northbound on Manhattan Place when it came to a stop to yield to an oncoming vehicle in a narrow roadway with parked vehicles on both sides of the street. As the oncoming SUV passed the Waymo AV, the driver’s side rear of the SUV made contact with the driver’s side rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV’s Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage and the SUV left the scene.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomy was stopped at a red traffic light on northbound Capp St at the intersection with 24th St in San Francisco. At that time, an SUV (Vehicle 2), heading southbound on Capp St, failed to stop for the red traffic light and entered the intersection, causing a collision with a passenger car (Vehicle 3) that was traveling eastbound on 24th Street. The SUV spun after making contact with the passenger car and collided with the stopped Zoox vehicle, damaging the front bumper on the driver’s side and driver’s side fender, mirror, and sensors on the Zoox vehicle. The police and EMS personnel were called to the scene. The driver of the SUV left the scene without exchanging information. The passenger car appeared to sustain significant damage to the front end. There were no reported injuries.
